gcc -E hello.c -o hello.i
this -E tell computer compile c program and stop after pre processing .i (intermediate file)
What does the preprocessor do?

Everything we've studied today happens here.

It performs:

✅ #include
✅ #define
✅ Macro expansion
✅ #ifdef
✅ #ifndef
✅ #if
✅ #elif
✅ #else
✅ defined()
✅ Removes comments

This is why I wanted you to study the preprocessor first.



---------------------------------------------
Stage 2 — Compiler

Input

hello.i

Output

hello.s

Command

gcc -S hello.c
What are the major phases inside the compiler?

Answer:

Lexical Analysis
Syntax Analysis
Semantic Analysis
Optimization
Code Generation
This generates assembly code.

The compiler:

Checks syntax
Performs type checking
Optimizes (depending on optimization flags)
Converts C into assembly
Stage 3 — Assembler

Input

hello.s

Output

hello.o

Command

gcc -c hello.c

The assembler converts assembly instructions into machine code and produces an object file (.o).

Stage 4 — Linker

Input

hello.o

Output

a.out

The linker:

Combines your object files.
Links library functions like printf.
Resolves symbols (functions and global variables).
Produces the final executable.

We'll study linking in depth later.

