The compilation stages are the same. What changes is the compiler, assembler, linker, and object file format, not the intermediate file extensions.

Let's compare.

Stage	    Linux (GCC/Clang)	Windows (GCC/MinGW)	    Windows (MSVC)	            macOS (Clang)
Source	        .c	                    .c	                .c	                         .c
Preprocessor	.i	                    .i              	.i (or internal)	         .i
Compiler	    .s	                    .s	                .asm (usually)	             .s
Assembler   	.o	                    .o (MinGW)	        .obj	                     .o
Linker      	a.out or executable	    .exe	            .exe                   a.out or executable



Another Important Difference

The object file format changes with the operating system.

OS	Object File Format
Linux	ELF (Executable and Linkable Format)
Windows	COFF / PE 
macOS	Mach-O



1. ELF

Full Form:

Executable and Linkable Format

This is the standard binary file format used by Linux and most Unix-like operating systems.

ELF is used for:

Executables
Object files (.o)
Shared libraries (.so)
Core dump files

Examples:

hello.o
libpthread.so
a.out
core

All of these are ELF files on Linux.

2. PE

Full Form:

Portable Executable

Used by:

Windows executables (.exe)
Windows DLLs (.dll)

Examples:

notepad.exe
kernel32.dll

PE is the Windows executable format.

3. COFF

Full Form:

Common Object File Format

Originally developed by AT&T.

Used for object files.

Microsoft later extended COFF into PE/COFF.

MSVC object files (.obj) use COFF.

4. Mach-O

Full Form:

Mach Object

Used by:

macOS
iOS

Examples:

Safari
Terminal
libSystem.dylib

All are Mach-O binaries.

Easy Interview Table
OS	Binary Format	Full Form
Linux	ELF	Executable and Linkable Format
Windows	PE	Portable Executable
Windows Object Files	COFF	Common Object File Format
macOS	Mach-O	Mach Object
⭐ Interview Question

Interviewer:

What is an ELF file?

Good answer:

ELF stands for Executable and Linkable Format. It is the standard binary format used by Linux for executables, object files, shared libraries, and core dumps. It contains sections such as .text, .data, .bss, symbol tables, relocation information, and metadata required by the linker and loader.

⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Another Interview Question

Interviewer:

Why is it called "Linkable" Format?

Because ELF is not only for executables.

The linker also works with:

main.o
utils.o
network.o

These are linkable object files.

The linker combines them into:

app

So ELF supports both:

Linkable files (.o)
Executable files

Hence the name:

Executable and Linkable Format

📝 Notes
ELF  = Executable and Linkable Format
PE   = Portable Executable
COFF = Common Object File Format
Mach-O = Mach Object

Linux  -> ELF
Windows -> PE / COFF
macOS -> Mach-O
